    "opinion": "As a 90-year-old retired man living in Chicago, I've seen many changes in how information spreads, from newspapers to television to this new social media. With my anxious nature and spending about an hour daily on these platforms, I've developed a cautious approach to managing fake content. First, I always check the source of information. If it comes from an unfamiliar website or someone I don't know personally, I'm immediately skeptical. I remember when newspapers had editors who verified facts before publishing, and I wish social media had more of that. Second, I look for consistency across multiple sources. If only one person is sharing a sensational story, it's probably not true. I've learned this through experience—many times, my grandchildren have shown me how false stories spread faster than true ones. Third, I avoid sharing anything unless I'm absolutely certain it's accurate. My Hindu beliefs emphasize truthfulness, and I don't want to contribute to misinformation. I also use the reporting features on social media when I see obvious fake content, though I worry they don't work quickly enough. My moderate conscientiousness score of 38 means I'm careful but not obsessive, so I balance vigilance with not letting it consume me. Living through decades of media evolution has taught me that critical thinking is the best defense. I discuss questionable posts with my wife or children before believing them, and I've taught my grandchildren to do the same. Ultimately, managing fake content requires patience, skepticism, and a commitment to truth—values that have served me well through 90 years of life in Chicago.",
